sometimes we need to undo a merge,
if we don't push yet and history is just local,
we can just move HEAD and branch pointer to the commit before merging.

but if we pushed, we should not never change history!
in this situation we should revert merge,
it means we should create "new" commit that is exactly opposite of merge commit.
(if the merge was ff, and we have not just a unique merge commit,
 we need revert them one by one!)

1.moving HEAD by "RESET"
  "git reset --hard HEAD~1"     //always use --soft!

imagine we are in 31a560a,
we will back to ec1a607

 *   31a560a conflict has resolved                  //merge commit always
 |\                                                 //has 2 pointer!
 | * 5c8ff89 (conflict-branch) simulate conflict
 * | ec1a607 simulate conflict
 |/
 * 118ef89 simulate conflict

Note: it make HEAD and current branch pointer move
      to pre commit on current branch.
      it means we will not move to 5c8ff89

Note: we have three options har d/soft/mixed
      HARD   means the commit/stage/working directory will returned to that point.
      SOFT   means just commit will returned to that point.
      MIXED  means commit/stage will returned to that point. (it's default)

Note: after moving Head and branch pointer to ec1a607,
      the merge commit (31a560a) will be a garbage!
      and garbage collector will remove it.
      but it takes some time, so we can move back the header to him
      before garbage collector remove it!
      (git reset --hard 31a560a)

